I feel like everyone in my house is best first thing in the morning. That time of the day, where we are the most collected and ready to embrace what lies ahead. I take this time to shower my family with love and if we can squeeze a sit down breakfast in before we start our day…. I take the opportunity with both hands and cherish it. #MorningsMeanMore
 
Lately Breakfast Sopes have been the morning meal of choice, especially now during the holiday season. 🎄✨🎄 They come together quicker than you’d think. Mix up the masa and in no time we are all biting into these crisp sopes topped with beans, eggs, salsa, avocado and @realcalifmilk dairy – Oaxaca cheese and Crema! This is the perfect way to start our day with an exquisite meal.
 
The other morning at breakfast my son asked me why my food taste so good compared to some other sopes he’s had elsewhere. I told him a lot has to do with the type of products I use. I look for the #RealCaliforniaMilk seal when choosing dairy because I know I’m spending my money on products that are made with sustainably sourced milk from California dairy families. Plus, the seal equates quality and that means all the difference to me.
 
Hopefully in the rush of the holidays you can steal a few calm and collected morning moments to just sit and enjoy delicious sopes with your favorite people on the planet.
 
Breakfast Sopes

Sopes:
2 cups masa harina

2 ½ cups Real California Oaxaca cheese, shredded

Poached Pear and Goat Cheese Tart!
Ingredients:
Crust:
1 1/3 cup all purpose flour
¼ teaspoon salt
½ cup salted butter, cold and sliced into pieces
5 tablespoons water, ice cold
Poached Pears:
3 bosc pears
2 bottles apple cider
1 cup water
½ cup brown sugar
1 tablespoon vanilla
Filling:
8.5 oz. goat cheese, room temp
1 egg
½ cup whipping or heavy cream
¼ teaspoon salt and pepper
Garnish:
Chopped hazelnuts, bluecheese crumbles, honey, dried cherry pieces
 
Directions:
Crust:
Place flour, salt, and butter in a food processor and pulse 8 times or until butter breaks up into the flour. Then add in water and pulse another 12 times. Dump mixture out of food processor into a clean kitchen towel and twist to make a beggars purse.
 
Roll dough out on a well floured surface an inch larger than the size of your tart pan. Transfer dough to tart pan and press it in to fit pan. Discard any excess dough.
 
Chill fitted dough in tart pan in the freezer for 30 minutes.
 
Preheat oven to 425 degrees Fahrenheit.
 
Poached Pears:
Peel and half pears by cutting down the middle length wise. Remove seeds in the middle of each half with a small spoon or ball scoop.
Bring apple cider, water, brown sugar, and vanilla to a boil in a large pot over a medium high heat. Add in pear halves and boil for 20 minutes or until fork tender but still in tact.
 
Remove from liquid and place on a cooling rack to dry and cool.
 
Filling:
Place all ingredients for filling in a food processor and pulse until creamy and smooth.
 
Pour filling into chilled tart pan, then place cooled pear halves on top.
 
Bake for 30 minutes.
 
Remove from oven and allow to cool for 10 minutes before topping with garnish.

Tacos Gobernador are probably the easiest tacos to make and easily the tastiest too. We enjoy them year round but especially during the Lent season when people observe meatless meals on Fridays.
 
For those of you that have never tried one… let me paint this picture for you. Tasty succulent shrimp is nestled between melty Real California Queso Quesadilla and wrapped in a crunchy corn tortilla shell.
 
I add the shrimp in raw and allow it to cook while the cheese melts. This makes for the perfect texture and avoids over-cooking the shrimp which can end up tasting rubbery. I add a little bit of salsa and little pieces of fried potato for extra flavor. The real star of the show is the Real California cheese which is added into the build of the taco twice.
 
You can use any melty cheese you’d like…Queso Quesadilla, Oaxaca, Asadero, Manchego…. As long as it has the Real California Milk Seal on it, you know you are getting quality cheese made from sustainably sourced milk from California dairy families = the best cheese for the best tacos. @realcalifmilk 
 
Here’s what I used:
 
10 large shrimp (peeled, cleaned, cut into ½ inch pieces)
½ cup salsa (use your favorite salsa – red or green, homemade or store bought)
6 corn tortillas
3 cups Real California Queso Quesadilla, grated
1 large potato (peeled, cut into ½ inch pieces, fried to a crisp)

Shrimp A La Veracruzana – A delicious meal for Lent. Buy all your ingredients at Northgate Gonzalez Market and have this dish on your table in no time.
 
3 tablespoons olive oil
1 cup onion
2 cups tomato, chopped
¼ cup pickled jalapenos
¼ cup green olives, chopped
3 cloves garlic, minced
1/2 cup Clamato
1 tablespoon Salsa Mexico Lindo 7 mares
1 lb. Mexican Shrimp, deveined and peeled
2 tablespoons cilantro, chopped
Lemon, sliced
 
Pour olive oil into a large frying pan over a medium high flame and allow to heat.
 
Saute onion and tomato for 5 minutes or until tomatoes are wilted and mushy.
 
Add in jalapenos, olives, and garlic. Sauté for an additional 2 minutes.
 
Pour in Clamato and Salsa Mexico Lindo 7 Mares and allow to simmer for 10 minutes.
 
Add in shrimp and cover with lid. Cook for 4 to 5 minutes or until the color changes to pink.
 
Spoon over white rice, sprinkle with cilantro and serve with lemon slices.

CARROT CAKE!!!!! One of the most popular dessert recipes during EASTER time. I added @parmalatusa Nata Crema para Desayunar to my batter for it’s creamy, silky smooth texture, and it 
doesn’t disappoint… it’s giving moist #CarrotCake for days. 🥕🥕🥕🥕
Easter is just a few away…. Lots of bunny love to you and yours. 🐰💝

Cake:
4 eggs
3/4 cups vegetable oil
2 cups sugar
3/4 cup Parmalat Nata
2 ¼ cups flour
2 teaspoons baking soda 
1 1/2 teaspoons cinnamon 
1/2 teaspoon ground ginger
1 teaspoon salt
2 teaspoons vanilla extract
2 cups grated carrots
1 cup shredded sweetened coconut
1/2 cup dried cherries 
1/2 cup chopped pistachios
Frosting: 
1/4 cup Parmalat Nata
1 cup butter (room temperature)
8 oz. cream cheese (room temperature)
3 1/3 cups powdered sugar
1 teaspoon salt
1 teaspoon vanilla 
Directions:
1. Preheat oven to 350 Fahrenheit.
2. Spray 3 - 8 inch cake pans with non stick baking spray. Set to the side.
3. In a mixer beat eggs and oil on medium speed to combine.
4. Add in sugar and mix for an additional minute.
5. Beat Parmalat Nata and vanilla into batter until well mixed.
5. Mix all dry ingredients in a separate bowl with a whisk.
6. Pour dry ingredients into mixer to combine with egg/sugar mixture. Mix until 
combined.
7. Next add in carrots, coconut, cherries, and pistachios. Mix until mixture is combined.
8. Divide batter into 3 equal parts amongst the prepared cake pans. It should measure out to 2 cups of cake batter per pan. 
9. Bake for 28 to 30 minutes or until toothpick comes out clean. Allow to cool 
completely.
Directions for Frosting:
1. In a mixer whip Nata, butter and cream cheese together until combined.
2. Add in sugar and salt and mix on medium speed until combined.
3. Lastly add in vanilla and mix until fully combined.
4. Ice cake.
5. Decorate top of cake as you wish. I used toasted coconut and malt ball candy for my #Easter theme.

BLUEBERRY PECAN COFFEE CAKE!!! This is the ultimate snacking cake. The kind you wish was hanging out in the house on any afternoon so you could get really friendly with it. What sets this coffee cake apart from the rest is the beautifully moist texture of the cake. Thanks to @parmalatusa Nata it stays moist until the cake is all gone, which always happens too fast! 
 
Pecan Streusel Topping:
2/3 cup packed brown sugar
1 cup all-purpose flour
2 teaspoons cinnamon
6 tablespoons butter, chilled
½ cup chopped pecans
 
Blueberry Cake:
½ cup vegetable oil
1 cup sugar
2 large eggs
1 tablespoon vanilla
2/3 cup Parmalat Nata
1 ½ cups all purpose flour
1 teaspoon baking powder
1/2 teaspoon baking soda
½ teaspoon salt
1 cup blueberries 🫐 
 
Icing:
1 cup confectioners sugar
2 tablespoons milk
¼ teaspoons vanilla extract
 
Directions:
Preheat oven to 350. 
 
Spray and parchment paper line 9-inch round pan with non-stick baking spray. Set to the side.
 
Pecan Streusel Topping: 
In a food processor combine brown sugar, flour, cinnamon, and butter. Pulse until combined and small pea shaped balls are formed. Remove mixture from food processor and place in a bowl. Mix in pecans to combine. Place mixture in refrigerator until ready to use.
 
Blueberry Cake: In a stand mixer fitted with a paddle attachment beat oil, sugar, eggs and vanilla on medium speed until combined. Using a rubber spatula scrape down sides of bowl, then add in Parmalat Nata and mix on medium speed to combine.  Whisk flour, baking powder, baking soda, and salt together in a separate bowl, then sprinkle it over the wet ingredients. Just mix until ingredients come together. Fold in blueberries.
 
Pour cake batter into the prepared baking pan, then sprinkle pecan streusel topping evenly over top.
 
Place cake on middle rack of oven and bake for 60 minutes or until toothpick inserted in the middle comes out clean.
 
Cool for 1 hour before removing cake from pan and placing on a serving plate.
 
Icing: Whisk all ingredients together and then drizzle icing over the top of the cake.

M is for May, Margaritas and Mangos! 🥭Since everyone loves mango- let’s kick off May with a Mangonada Margarita.
 
Tequila Blanco (silver) is ideal for this drink. The young tequila doesn’t carry the aged notes that a Gold Tequila (Reposado) does, so it allows the flavors of agave and mango to really compliment one another.
 
Chamoy, Tajin, and Banderillas de Tamarindo: These are key ingredients to this drink.
We certainly can not make a Mangonada without chamoy. Chamoy is a Mexican condiment made of dried fruit, chile, sugar, salt and lime. There are many different chamoy brands on the market and it’s popularity is making it really easy to find.
Tajin is a chile-lime seasoning, adding that perfect chile acidic balance to the drink.
Banderillas de Tamarindo are like little chile sticks, made with natural tamarind fruit candy that wraps around a straw. There’s no better way to suck down a Mangonada Margarita than through a banderilla de tamarindo.
 
Mangonada Margarita:
 
Prep: 10 minutes
Freeze: 3 hours minimum
Yields: 4 margaritas
 
Ingredients:
3 large mangos, peeled and cubed (about 6 cups)
1 cup ice
3 tablespoons sugar
2 limes, 1  juiced and 1 sliced for garnish
½ cup tequila blanco (silver)
½ cup Chamoy
¼ cup Tajin
4 banderillas de tamarindo – Tamarind Fruit Candy Straw
 
Directions:
 
Peel and chop mangos into 1 inch cubes.
Place in a giant airtight freezer bag and place in the freezer for a minimum of 3 hours but ideally overnight.
 
Pour 4 cups of frozen mango cubes into a blender with ice, sugar, 1 juiced lime, and tequila.
Blend until smooth.
 
On two small plates, fill one plate with chamoy, and fill the other plate with Tajin.
Dip the rim of each margarita glass in the chamoy first then coat the rim in the Tajin to seal in the Chamoy.
 
Fill the bottom of each cup with 3 tablespoons of chamoy.
Then evenly divide the mango margarita mixture amongst the 4 cups.
 
Garnish each glass with  ½ cup of frozen mango cubes, ¼ of a teaspoon of tajin, a lime slice, a drizzle of chamoy, and a banderilla. ¡SALUD!

Rajas con Jocoque SKINS
 
Ingredients:
6 medium sized potatoes
8 tablespoons butter, divided
½ teaspoon salt
¼ garlic powder
½ teaspoon black pepper
1 ½ cups grated cheese
1 poblano chile
2 anaheim chiles
1 yellow bell pepper
1 white onion, sliced into long strips.
1 cup corn kernels
3 garlic cloves, minced
1/3 cup hot water
1 12 oz. container @parmalatusa Jocoque Seco Natural
 
Directions:
 
Preheat oven to 425 degrees Fahrenheit.
 
Clean potatoes by scrubbing them under water. Poke the potatoes with a fork several times on each side.
 
Bake potatoes for 50 – 60 minutes or until fork tender.
 
While potatoes are baking, roast poblano chile, Anaheim chiles, and yellow bell pepper on an open flame until charred on all sides. Place roasted chiles and yellow bell pepper in an airtight bag and allow to steam in their own heat for 30 minutes.
 
Peel charred skin off chiles and pepper, by scraping with a butterknife. Cut each chile and bell pepper into thin strips.
 
Melt 3 tablespoons butter in a large frying pan over a medium flame. Saute chile, bell pepper, onion slices and corn in butter for 10 to 15 minutes or until onion is limp. Add in minced garlic and saute for an additional 3 minutes. Mixing often to ensure garlic doesn’t burn. Pour in hot water and season with salt and pepper to taste.
 
Mix in Parmalat Jocoque Natural into the rajas mixture until well incorporated. Set to the side until ready to use.
 
Remove potatoes from oven and allow to cool enough to handle.
 
Cut each potato lengthwise and scrape out most of the flesh using a small spoon, leaving a ¼ inch around the rim.  
 
Place 5 tablespoons butter, salt, garlic powder, and ground pepper in a bowl and microwave for 30 seconds or until the butter is melted.
 
Brush the potatoes inside and out with melted butter mixture.
 
Then place the brushed potato skins on a baking sheet cut side down and bake for 15 minutes.
Remove from oven and flip the potatoes around. Fill each potato with 2 tablespoons of cheese. Place back in oven for 7 minutes to allow cheese to melt and edges of potatoes to get extra toasty.
 
Remove from oven and fill each with Rajas con Jocoque!

Gelatin De Pitaya Con Crema Mosaico: Get your pitayas at @northgatemarket from now to June! You don’t want to sleep on this delicious #gelatinadepitaya 
 
Ingredients:
Pitaya Gelatina:
• 2 cups Pitaya pulp – 5 pitayas, peeled and pureed
• ¾ cup boiling hot water
• 3 (.25 ounce) packets unflavored gelatin
• 1 cup sugar
Crema Gelatina:
• 4 (.25 ounce) packets unflavored gelatin
• ¾ cup boiling hot water
• 1 (14 ounce) can sweetened condensed milk
• 1 (12 ounce) can evaporated milk
• 2 cups milk
• ½ cup sugar
Pink Gelatina:
• 2 (.25 ounce) packets unflavored gelatin
• ½ cup boiling hot water
• 1 1/2 cups milk
• 1 pitaya, peeled and pureed
• ½ cup sugar
 
Directions:
Pitaya Gelatin:
1. Sprinkle unflavored gelatin in hot water and mix to dissolve. Set to the side.
2. Add sugar and Pitaya pulp to a pan over a medium heat. Mix to combine until all the sugar is dissolved. Stir in unflavored gelatin mixture until completely incorporated.
3. Spray a 2 quart glass baking dish with nonstick cooking spray. Pour in Pitaya gelatin. Refrigerate for 3 hours or until firm.
 
Crema Gelatin:
1. Begin crema gelatin 45 minutes before pitaya gelatin is done firming up. Sprinkle unflavored gelatin in hot water and mix to dissolve. Set to the side.
2. Heat remaining crema gelatin ingredients over a low heat until sugar dissolves.
3. Remove from heat and stir in unflavored gelatin mixture until completely incorporated.
4. Pour ½ cup crema gelatin mixture in a lightly greased 12 cup bundt pan and refrigerate for 30 minutes.
 
Assembly:
1. Cut Pitaya gelatin into squares. Place cubes in bundt pan over crema gelatin. Pour remaining crema gelatin mixture over pitaya gelatin cubes. Refrigerate for 1 hour.
 
Pink Gelatina:
1. Sprinkle unflavored gelatin in hot water and mix to dissolve. Set to the side.
2. Add sugar and Pitaya pulp to a pan over a medium heat. Mix to combine until all the sugar is dissolved. Stir in milk and unflavored gelatin mixture until completely incorporated.
3. Remove from heat and allow to come to room temperature.
4. Pour on top of crema gelatin layer.
5. Refrigerate for 5 hours or overnight.

Jocoque Asparagus Tart:
 
2 sheets frozen puff pastry
2 eggs, divided
1 teaspoon water
3 garlic cloves
1 cup Parmalat Jocoque Seco
½ cup grated parmesan cheese
¼ teaspoon truffle salt
¼ teaspoon ground black pepper
¼ cup green onion, sliced
1 lb asparagus, washed and trimmed
2 tablespoons olive oil
2 tablespoons honey
2 tablespoons pistachios, chopped
 
Preheat oven to 400 degrees Fahrenheit.
 
Lightly grease a large baking sheet. Set to the side.
 
Roll pastry sheet out on a lightly floured clean surface with a rolling pin.
 
Cut each sheet into 6 equal rectangles, for a total of 12.
 
Whisk 1 egg and 1 teaspoon water in a small bowl to create egg wash.
 
Using a sharp knife, gently score a 1/2” border, only cutting through half the pastry. Poke the inside of the border with a fork making pricks all over the area.
 
Brush each pastry rectangle with egg wash.
 
Place rectangles on baking sheet and bake in the oven for 5 minutes allowing the pastries to form a slightly raised border.
 
Meanwhile while pastry is baking, add garlic to a food processor and pulse until garlic is minced. Add in @parmalatusa Jocoque Seco, and pulse to combine. Add in 1 egg, parmesan cheese, truffle salt, and black pepper. Pulse to combine. Lastly add in green onion and give it one pulse to lightly combine.
 
Spread two tablespoons of jocoque mixture evenly across center of each rectangle. Making sure to stay within the raised border.
 
Divide asparagus into 12 portions and arrange 1 portion of asparagus per pastry rectangle. Making sure to stay with the border.
 
Lightly drizzle oil oil over all pastry then place back in the oven for 20 minutes.
 
Remove from oven and drizzle with honey and sprinkle chopped pistachios over the top. Serves 12.

• 2 cups sugar
• 15 strawberries, stems removed

What makes these fried shrimp the crunchiest and most scrumptious is the way I batter them. I use flour, Parmalat Jocoque Seco, and panko. This combo creates a delicious crunch when fried instead of a cakey doughy coating. I highly recommend it. The dad in your life will be so happy you did.
 
Fried Shrimp and Fries with Parmalat Jalapeño Jocoque Seco
 
1 1/2 cups all purpose flour
1 teaspoon salt
1 teaspoon black pepper
12 oz. Parmalat Jocoque Seco
3 tablespoons mineral water
2 cups panko
24 jumbo shrimp- peeled and deveined
4 large potatoes- peeled, cut into wedges and boiled for 10 minutes
1 teaspoon garlic powder
2 teaspoons seasoning salt
1 gallon vegetable oil
12 oz. Parmalat Jalapeño Cheddar Jocoque Seco
1 lemon, cut into wedges
 
 
Set up dipping station with 3 bowls.
Mix flour, salt and pepper together in bowl number 1.
Mix Parmalat Jocoque Seco and mineral water together in bowl number 2.
Pour panko in bowl number 3.
 
Dip shrimp in flour to cover, then dredge in jocoque to cover, and lastly cover in panko. Repeat until all shrimp are coated.
Place coated shrimp on a parchment paper lined tray and place in the freezer for 30 minutes minimum.
 
Sprinkle boiled potato wedges with garlic powder and seasoning salt. Mix to evenly coat.
 
Heat vegetable oil in a deep fryer to 375 degrees Fahrenheit.
 
Deep fry shrimp for 2 ½ to 3 minutes or until coating is golden crisp.
Deep fry potato wedge fries for 5 to 7 minutes depending on how crispy you like them.
 
Drain shrimp and fries on a paper towel lined tray.
Serve immediately with lemon wedges and #Parmalat Jalapeño Cheddar Jocoque Seco as the most delicious dipping spread.

Ingredients:
 
• 36 oz. Parmalat Nata
• 2 cups sugar
• 4 cups fresh strawberries, chopped
• 3 tablespoons unsweetened chocolate powder
• 1 cup milk chocolate chips
• 1 ½ cups shortbread cookie crumbles
• 12 (9oz) paper cups
• 12 popsicle sticks
 
Directions:
 
Mix 24 oz. of Parmalat Nata with 1 cup of sugar. Mix until fully incorporated and sugar granules have dissolved. Set to the side.
 
Pour ½ cup sugar over strawberries and mix to combine. Allow the sugar and strawberries to rest for 10 minutes. They will become a bit syrupy.
 
Gently fold the strawberries into the sweet Nata mixture. You will use this mixture for two layers of each paleta.
 
Make the Chocolate layer: Heat ½ cup sugar, 12 oz. Parmalat Nata, unsweetened chocolate powder, and milk chocolate chips together over a low flame until smooth. Mix constantly to keep Nata from burning. This should take about 5 minutes. Remove from flame and bring to room temperature.
 
Assemble:
Place ¼ cup Strawberries and Nata at the bottom of each cup. Place in freezer for 1 hour to firm.
Then spoon in ¼ cup Chocolate Nata over the Strawberries and Nata Layer. Insert a popsicle stick in the middle and place in the freezer for 30 minutes to firm.
Top with an additional ¼ cup Strawberries and Nata. Sprinkle top with 2 tablespoons of shortbread crumbles, then gently press top with fingers.
Place in freezer over night or a minimum of 8 hours.
 
Unmold by tearing paper cup off paleta.
Enjoy. ❤️

With temperatures reaching 90+, it’s too hot to turn on the oven these days. Craving something sweet? Make this Summer dessert!  NO BAKE PEACH 🍑 CHEESECAKE. Thanks to the use of Parmalat Nata it’s the creamiest cheesecake I’ve ever had.
Crust:
2 cups graham cracker crumbs
1/4 cup brown sugar, packed
1 stick salted butter, melted
Cheesecake:
16 oz. cream cheese, room temperature
1 cup powdered sugar
1 (4.2 oz) package peach gelatin
3/4 cup Parmalat Nata
1 1/2 cups heavy cream
Topping:
3 cups peaches, sliced (4 peaches)
½ cup turbinado sugar
1 teaspoon vanilla
1 tablespoon butter
¼ cup cold water
½ tablespoon cornstarch
 
Pulse graham crackers and brown sugar in food processor until you have a fine crumb. The moisture in the brown sugar will help solidify the crust. Pour in melted butter and mix until well combine. 
 
Pour graham cracker crumb mixture into a 9 inch springform pan. Press the crumbs firmly to cover bottom and sides of pan. Place in the freezer while you prep the filling.
 
Beat cream cheese and powdered sugar together with mixer on medium speed until combined about 2 minutes. Add in peach gelatin and mix for 3 minutes. Add in 3/4 cup Parmalat Nata and mix for an additional 2 minutes. Pour mixture into a large mixing bowl.
 
Whisk heavy cream in mixer on high until peaks form. 
Gently fold whipped cream into Nata and cream cheese mixture. 
 
Pour Nata / whipped cream mixture into prepared springform pan. Smooth the top with an offset spatula. Place in the fridge for a minimum of 8 hours or overnight to firm.
 
Place sliced peaches, sugar, and vanilla in a large bowl and mix to combine. Allow the sugars to draw the liquid from the peaches for 30 minutes before removing the liquid from the bowl and placing the liquid in a small pot over a medium heat. Add in butter, and bring to a simmer.
Mix cornstarch with water until dissolved. Pour cornstarch slurry into peach liquid and mix to combine. Once mixture thickens remove from heat, and pour over sliced peaches. Mix to combine.
 
Once the cheesecake is set, gently spoon peach mixture over the top of cheesecake.

Let me share one of my favorite breakfast meals… Overnight Oats! I use Parmalat Nata for the creamiest Overnight Oats. It consists of a mixture of Nata, milk, old fashioned rolled oats, banana, chopped almonds, and chia. I whip up a big batch at night, pour in several airtight jars, place in the refrigerator, and have breakfast ready to go all week long.
 
Adding Nata to the mixture creates a super creamy, not soupy or watery, mixture that melts in your mouth. Add a dollop of peanut butter to the top, a drizzle of agave, and a few chocolate chips. It’s so delicious… it’s like a morning dessert and it only took a few minutes to make. ENJOY!

Overnight Oats Ingredients:
 
1 ripe banana, mashed
1 ½ cups Parmalat milk
¾ cup Parmalat Nata
2 tablespoons honey or agave + more for top drizzle
½ tablespoon vanilla
¼ teaspoon salt
¼ cup chopped almonds
1 tablespoon chia seeds
1 ½ cups Old Fashioned Rolled Oats
Peanut butter and chocolate chips optional
 
In a large mixing bowl, mash banana until pureed, then whisk in Parmalat Milk, Parmalat Nata, vanilla, agave, and salt to combine. Fold in chia seeds, chopped almonds, and old fashioned rolled oats together with creamy mixture.
 
Spoon 1 cup into each jar, soak overnight for a minimum of 8 hours.
 
Oats will expand 10 % do not fill to the brim.
 
When ready to eat sprinkle top with chocolate chips, agave and a dollop of peanut butter.

September calls for Mexican Chocolate Cake!
It’ll have you doing your best grito and running to get Parmalat Nata for the dreamiest chocolate cake EVER. It’s so good, I almost didn’t want to share the recipe. Hope you enjoy this gem!
 
 
Mexican Chocolate Cake
 
Cake:
 
2 cups all purpose flour
1/2 cup unsweetened cocoa powder, packed
1 ½ teaspoons baking powder
1 teaspoon baking soda
½ teaspoon salt
1 teaspoon ground cinnamon
2 cups sugar
2 large eggs
½ cup milk
¾ cup Parmalat Nata
½ cup vegetable oil
2 tsp vanilla extract
½ cup boiling hot coffee
1/4 cup Mexican chocolate, grated
 
Frosting:
 
1/2 cup Parmalat Nata
1 cup unsalted butter, softened
2 teaspoons vanilla extract
½ teaspoon salt
1/2 cup unsweetened cocoa powder, packed
2 ½ cups powdered sugar
Mexican chocolate powder for garnish
 
Preheat oven to 350 degrees
 
Line a 13x9 metal pan with parchment paper with excess overlap for easy removal.
 
Whisk flour, cocoa powder, baking powder, baking soda, salt, cinnamon, and sugar together until combined on a low speed.
 
Mix in eggs, milk, Parmalat Nata, vegetable oil, and vanilla on a medium speed. Once combined, slowly pour in hot coffee while mixer is mixing on low speed.
 
Fold Mexican chocolate into batter.
 
Pour cake batter into baking pan and smooth top.
 
Bake for 45- 50 minutes or until toothpick comes out clean.
 
Allow cake to cool completely for a minimum of 3 hours.
 
Make Frosting: Beat Parmalat Nata, butter, and vanilla on medium high until completely combined. Add in salt and cocoa powder mix on low to combine. Add in powdered sugar and mix on low until combined, once combined mix on medium high for 1 minute.
 
Swirl frosting on top of cake until completely covered, then sprinkle Mexican chocolate powder over the top. Enjoy!
 
• If you refrigerate the cake after frosting the frosting will become thick and melt in your mouth. It is a preference by the individual.

Bandera Mexicana Dip:
 
1 cup walnuts,
24 oz. Parmalat Jocoque Natural
2 poblano chile – 1 ½ cups
1 cup red apple, chopped into small cubes
1 cup peach, chopped into small cubes
¼ cup almonds, chopped
¼ teaspoon salt

Heat a pan or comal over a medium high flame.
Toast walnut in pan for 3 to 5 minutes mixing often.

‘Rajas con Coditos’ = a delicious Mexican style stovetop mac and cheese.
‘Coditos’ is how you say elbow pasta in Spanish.
 
What I love about this meal is the mild spice from the poblano chile strips (rajas) dotted with bits of yellow corn in a creamy cheese sauce. It’ll make you lick your lips twice. 🤤
This is one of the tastiest meals and a great way to celebrate Latino Heritage Month.
 
Rajas Con Coditos:
 
• 1 teaspoon vegetable oil
• 7 poblano chiles
• 1 lb. elbow/macaroni pasta (coditos), cooked according to package- al dente
• 4 tablespoons butter
• 1 large white onion, sliced  – 1 ½ cups
• 4 garlic cloves, minced – 2 tablespoons
• 1 ½ cup yellow corn – fresh or frozen
• ½ teaspoon salt
• ½ teaspoon ground pepper
• 2 cups broth – chicken or vegetable
• 1 cup Crema Con Sal
• 1 1/2 cups Chihuahua cheese, grated
• 1 ½ cups Monterey Jack cheese, grated
• Optional – crushed chile flakes
 
 
Directions:
 
Rub poblano chiles with a little bit of vegetable oil to coat. Place chiles on an open flame to char the skin. Once each entire chile is charred, place in an airtight plastic container/bag and seal. Allow chiles to steam in their own heat for 20 to 30 minutes.
 
Cook coditos (elbow pasta) according to box (7-8 minutes). Strain and place to the side.
 
Remove chiles from bag and scrape off all the charred skin with a butterknife. Remove the stem and slit the chile down the side and remove all the seeds from the inside of the chile. Then thinly slice the poblano chile into 1/8 inch wide strips.
 
In a large pan or pot over a medium high flame melt butter, then add in sliced onion and poblano chile strips. Sauté for 10 minutes mixing occasionally.
 
Mix in garlic, corn, salt and pepper and cook sauté for an additional 3 minutes.
 
Pour in broth and crema and mix to combine. Allow the liquid to come to a slight boil, this should take 5 minutes, then add in coditos (elbow pasta), and both cheeses. Mix until all the cheese melts.
 
Sprinkle crushed chile flakes on top and serve.

Placed them on a tray and started to build my snacking board with lots of Pan De Muerto, fruit, nuts, candy, cheese. All the things that I hope will bring my ancestors spirits around for even a little while.
 
Pan De Muerto Strips: Toast in oven at 350 for 10 minutes or fry in a pan with a small amount of butter until golden.
 
Chocolate Sauce: Melt 3 Mexican Chocolate tablets in a small sauce pan over a medium heat with 1/2 cup crema. Mix until fully combined and smooth.
 
Crema y Miel: Mix 1/2 cup crema and 1/2 cup honey together until combined.
 
Roasted Grapes: Bake stemless grapes on a lined baking sheet at 425 degrees Fahrenheit for 15 minutes or until blistered.

Sink your FORK into this frightfully delicious VAMPIRE FANG CAKE. 🧛‍♂️ Tender white cake is infused with red blood (strawberry gelatin) that is sure to entice every vampire lurking in the dark.
The little bloodsuckers will be thrilled to know that I used Parmalat Nata in the cake for a fine crumb and in the SWEET WHITE Icing to make it extra creamy. Monsters now have a special cake to be haunted by how wonderful it is!
 
What SPOOKY meal will BE eating you this Halloween?
 
 
Vampire Fang Cake:
Cake:
• 15.25 oz white cake mix
• ¾ cup Parmalat Nata
• 4 large egg whites
• ½ cup vegetable oil
• ¼ cup milk
• 6 oz. Strawberry or cherry gelatin powder
• 1 cup boiling hot water
Icing:
• ½ cup Parmalat Nata
• 1 cup unsalted butter, softened
• ½ teaspoon salt
• 4 cups powdered sugar
• 2 teaspoons milk
• 2 tablespoons cherry jam
 
 
Preheat oven to 350 degrees Fahrenheit.
 
Spray a 13x9 baking pan with a non-stick baking spray on the inside entirely. Make sure to spray the bottom and sides as well.
 
Add cake mix, Parmalat Nata, egg whites, vegetable oil, and milk to a stand-up mixer, and mix on low for a few seconds until all ingredients combine. Then beat batter on medium high for an additional 2 minutes.
 
Pour batter into prepared pan and smooth out top with a rubber spatula.
 
Bake in oven for 40 minutes, turning at the halfway mark for even baking. Cake is ready when toothpick inserted into the center comes out clean.
 
Allow to cool or 10 minutes, then poke holes with a chopstick all over the top of the cake.  
 
Mix gelatin and hot water in a bowl until gelatin is completely dissolved.
 
Pour gelatin mixture over the warm cake. Allow to come to room temperature.
 
Place in fridge for a minimum of 2 hours to set.
Make Icing:
 
Beat Parmalat Nata, butter, and milk on medium high until completely combined. Add in salt and powdered sugar and mix on low until combined, once combined mix on medium high for 1 minute.
 
Swirl frosting on top of cake until completely covered, then splatter cherry jam on top.
 
Bite in it when ready to eat!

Pumpkin Empanadas! Cute 🎃. Empanadas de Calabaza made with @parmalatusa Nata. You’re so funny with a big mouth. I’m not scared, but you are.
Empanada Dough:
• 3 cups all purpose flour
• 1/4 cup sugar
• 1 1/2 teaspoons salt
• 1/3 cup frozen vegetable shortening, spooned into teaspoon drops
• 2 ½ sticks (10 oz.) salted butter, cut into tabs, frozen
• 1/2 cup cold water
• Empanada Filling:
• 1 cup sugar
• ½ cup Parmalat Nata
• ½ cup pumpkin pie filling
• Egg Wash:
• 1 egg
• 1 tablespoon water
• 6 teaspoons Turbinado Sugar
 
For the crust:
Place the flour, sugar and salt into a food processor. Pulse to combine.
Add in vegetable shortening, and pulse until vegetable shortening is cut into the flour.
Pulse in frozen butter. Do not over pulse. You are looking for pea sized balls of butter to remain.
Slowly add in the ice water.
Dump the dough onto a clean surface. Quickly press the dough together to form a long log. Divide the log in half, and form each half into a disk.
Wrap each disk in plastic wrap and place in the fridge overnight.
Filling: Mix ½ cup sugar with ½ cup Parmalat Nata until completely combined.
Mix ½ cup sugar with ½ cup pumpkin pie filling until completely combined.
Egg Wash: Whisk egg and water together in a small bowl and set to the side.
Assemble Empanadas: Preheat oven to 425 degrees Fahrenheit.  
Roll one disk dough to a 1/8 inch thickness on a floured surface.  I roll it out to 14x12 inches, then cut dough with a 3 inch pumpkin shaped cookie cutter. Cut out ‘Jack o’ lantern’ faces on half of the amount of pumpkin cutouts. This will allow ventilation in each empanada.
Fill each piece (of the whole pumpkin dough) in the center with 1 tablespoon of Parmalat Nata filling and 1 tablespoon pumpkin filling.
Then carefully place ‘Jack o’ lantern’ face cutout on top of filling.
Place 6 empanadas two inches apart on a cookie sheet lined with parchment paper and crimp the edges of the dough with a fork.
Brush each empanada with egg wash, and sprinkle the top with turbinado sugar.
Bake for 18 to 20 minutes.
Remove from oven and place on cooling rack to cool for 10 minutes.

Who’s ready for Thanksgiving? Friendsgiving? Holiday parties? Potato Bacon Jocoque Bites will get you invited to all the hoilday parties year after year, with the request that you bring these delicous appetizers along for the crowd! Crispy potato stacks layered with, bacon, Parmalat Jocoque Chipotle, and cheese! 
 
Potato Jocoque Bacon Bites:
3 large potatoes
12 oz. @parmalatusa Jocoque Chipotle
¾ cup heavy cream
1 lb. bacon, cooked according to packaging
¼ cup chives, chopped
2 cup cheddar cheese, grated
½ cup butter, melted
 
Preheat oven to 400 degrees Fahrenheit.
Line a 8 ½  x 4 ½ x 2 ½ loaf pan with enough parchment paper to overlap pan.
Peel potatoes, and rinse under cold water to remove any dirt residue.
Slice potatoes to 1/16 inch rounds. Using a mandoline will keep this portion of the recipe uniform in size.
Whisk Parmalat Jocoque Chipotle with ¾ cup heavy cream until completely combined. Set to the side.
Place a single layer of potato slices at the bottom of prepared pan.
Add a heaping dollop of the Jocoque Chipotle cream mixture to the top of the potato slices. Brush it with a pastry brush to evenly coat potato slices. OR you could brush each potato slice individually to ensure they are coated. Whichever method works for you.
Layer in bacon slices, sprinkle with a ½ tablespoon chopped chives, and crumble in 1/3 cup grated cheddar cheese.
Repeat layering process with potato coated Jocoque slices, bacon, chives, cheddar cheese until all ingredients are used. Pour butter over the top and bake for 50 minutes.
Remove loaf pan from oven and carefully place overlapped parchment over the top of the loaf pan to cover. Then place heavy weighted cans over the entire pan to weigh down the contents inside. Allow to come to room temperature then place in fridge overnight.
Preheat oven to 400 degrees Fahrenheit.
Remove weights and carefully remove potatoes from pan. Discard parchment paper and slice into cubes 1 inch cubes.  Insert a toothpick into the center of each cube.
Place cubes on a parchment lined baking sheet and bake for 30 minutes or until golden crisp.

This Crunchy Mac and Cheese absolutely deserves a space at your holiday table. Loaded with flavor…the cheese sauce is so darn finger lickin yum…. I say the @parmalatusa Jocoque, used to make the creamy base is the perfect binder to tie in all the flavors of this mac and cheese recipe! It’s beyond…. Really! You gotta try it. ❤️
 
Crunchy Mac and Cheese
 
2 cups cherry tomatoes, halved
2 tablespoons olive oil
1 lb. macaroni pasta, cooked al-dente according to the package
½ cup butter + more for greasing pan
2 cups baby bella mushrooms, sliced
1 tablespoon Dijon mustard
5 garlic cloves, minced
6 stalks green onion, thinly sliced
12 oz. Parmalat Jocoque Seco, Natural
2 cups ½ and ½
3 cups cheddar cheese, grated
1/2 teaspoon truffle salt
5 basil leaves, cut into strips
2 cups potato chips, crushed
½ cup parmesan cheese
 
Blister Tomatoes: Heat olive oil in a large frying pan over a medium high flame. Add in halved tomatoes and sauté on each side for 5 minutes or until blistered. Remove from heat and set to the side until ready.
 
Cheese Sauce: Melt 4 tablespoons butter in a pot over a medium high heat. Add in mushrooms and sauté for 8 to 10 minutes or until mushrooms start to brown slightly. Add in mustard and mix to combine. Sprinkle in garlic and green onions. Sauté for 3 minutes or until mixture is fragrant. Lower flame to medium low heat and mix in Parmalat Jocoque until combined. Pour in ½ and ½ and mix until fully incorporated. Sprinkle in cheese and salt and mix until cheese melts and the mixture is smooth. Cut in basil strips and mix.
 
Add cooked macaroni and blistered tomatoes to cheese sauce, mix until fully combined.
Grease a 9x13 glass baking dish with butter, then pour macaroni mixture in baking dish. Sprinkle the top evenly with crushed potato chips and parmesan cheese.
Bake at 375 degress Fahrenheit for 40 minutes.
Enjoy!

Avena (Mexican oatmeal)
 
2 cups water
1 cinnamon stick
¼ cup gala apple, minced
¼ cup yellow raisins
½ teaspoon vanilla
2 cups old fashioned oats
1/8 teaspoon salt
3 cups Real California Milk
¼ cup sugar
 
Garnish:
Pepitas
Raisins
Dried Cranberries
Dried Cherries
Ground cinnamon
Real California milk
 
 
 
Add water, cinnamon stick, gala apple, raisins, and vanilla to a pot over a medium high heat and bring to a boil.
 
Sprinkle in oats and salt and mix to combine. Lower heat to medium low and allow to cook for 3 to 4 minutes or until water almost evaporates completely.
 
Pour in Real California milk and mix to combine. Lower heat to low and allow oats to simmer for 7 minutes. Mixing occasionally. Remove cinnamon stick.
Mix in sugar until it dissolves.
 
Divide avena equally into 4 bowls.
 
Garnish with pepitas, raisins, dried cranberries, dried cherries, ground cinnamon, and an extra splash of Real California Milk.
Serve with toast!

We all want our holiday baking to be perfect, and especially when you’re making dessert for a sit down dinner. Let Parmalat Nata help you make the creamiest flan you’ve ever had. This dessert works for the entire holiday season.
 
1 ¼ cups sugar
8 oz. @parmalatusa Nata
1 cup Pumpkin puree
4 eggs
1 teaspoon vanilla extract
1 can evaporated milk – 12 oz
1 can sweetened condensed milk
¼ teaspoon pumpkin spice
 
Preheat oven to 350 degrees Fahrenheit.
Pour sugar into a heavy-bottom sauce pan over a medium-high heat. After a few minutes the sugar will start to melt. Do not stir. Swirl sugar in pan in order to break up any sugar clumps. Once the sugar is melting reduce the heat to medium-low until all the sugar turns a light copper color, swirling the sugar in the pan occasionally. It will take between 5 to 10 minutes for the sugar to become caramel.
Evenly pour the caramel into 6 ramekins. Quickly swirl the caramel to coat the entire bottom of each ramekin. Set to the side and allow to cool.
Add Parmalat Nata, pumpkin puree, eggs, vanilla extract, evaporated milk, sweetened condensed milk, and pumpkin spice to a blender. Blend for 23minutes or until smooth.
Pour 1 cup of blended flan mixture into each ramekin over cooled caramel. Firmly press each ramekin with a piece of aluminum foil to cover the top.
Place all covered ramekins in a large baking dish. Then pour boiling hot water into the baking dish to create a bain-marie (water bath), filling the baking dish with about an 1 ½ inches of water.
Bake for 1 hour.
Remove large baking dish from oven.  Then carefully remove each ramekin from the hot water and place on a clean surface to cool for 30 minutes. Remove the aluminum foil tops and with a butter knife, run it along the edge of each ramekin to loosen the flan from the dish.
Place a small plate on top of each ramekin then flip to invert flan onto the plate. Gently lift up the ramekin and allow all caramel to drip out of ramekin. Continue with the rest of the ramekins.
Once flans are plated place in the fridge for a minimum of 4 hours to cool.
Decorate with pepitas and pomegranate seeds, optional.

Tablias de chocolate (Chocolate tablets) are a staple in most Mexican households as they are used in sweet and savory foods, such as hot chocolate and mole. The traditional blend for tablias de chocolate comprises roasted and peeled cacao, sugar, and cinnamon.  In my region, we add almonds, just as my friend Neto does, adding a creamy and natural nutty sweetness to it. Our ancestors used to make them using a metate (a volcanic stone tool for grinding and processing foods) called chocolate de metate. Still, thanks to motorized molinos like my friend’s, it’s possible to make your own tablias de chocolate.  Even then, it’s still labor-intensive, as you must process the blend, weigh it, and quickly mold it before it hardens.

When tamal season hits, my tias run to @northgatemarket to buy their masa preparada! It’s how we spice the masa at home that give our tamales that traditional family taste. Adding 1 cup of salsa to every 5 pounds of masa, and mixing it till it’s well combined.
For pork or chicken tamales we season the masa with a Tomatillo Salsa Verde. When we make shredded beef or frijol y queso tamales then we spice the masa with a chile rojo. How does your family season masa preparada? ♥️🫔♥️
 
Tomatillo Salsa Verde:
1 tablespoon oil
1 ½ lbs. tomatillos, husks removed and rinsed
2 serrano peppers, stems removed
1/4 of a medium onion
3 garlic cloves
4 cups chicken
4 poblano chiles
1 cup cilantro
1 tablespoon salt
6 peppercorns
 
Roast poblano chiles over an open flame until charred. This should take about 10 minutes. Place in an airtight bag to sweat for 20 minutes.
 
In a large frying pan over a medium high heat add in 1 tablespoon oil.
Add tomatillos, serrano peppers, and onion to pan. Saute in oil for 5 minutes or until tomatillos, peppers, and onion pieces are spotted. Add in garlic cloves and continue to brown for 5 additional minutes.
 
Pour in broth and and allow mixture to simmer for 20 minutes on low.
 
Remove Poblano chiles from bag and remove stem and charred skin by scrapping chile with a butter knife.
 
Add tomatillo with broth mixture, poblano chiles, cilantro, salt, and peppercorns to blender.
Blend until smooth. Makes: 8 cups
 
 
Chile Rojo
2.5 oz. New Mexico Chile
2.5 oz. California Chile
1 oz. Pasilla- Ancho Chiles
2.5 oz. Chile Guajillo
1 medium white onion
5 garlic cloves
1/2 tablespoon salt
 
Bring water  to a boil In a large pot filled halfway. Add chiles and onion. Boil for 30 minutes or until chiles soften. Reserve boiled chile water for later use.
 
Remove chiles from water and discard stem of each chile.
 
Place chiles, onion, garlic, salt and 3 cups of boiled chile water to blender. Blend until smooth.
 
Pour chile sauce mixture through a sieve and into a bowl. Press chile flesh against sieve to squeeze out all liquid from remnants of chile. Makes: 6 ½ cups

This hectic holiday season has me craving a bit of space to slow down and reflect. I’ve carved out my morning time to pause and appreciate the day ahead. #MorningsMeanMore when I can take that time and pair it with a Creamy Banana Atole. 
 
This traditional Mexican drink warms my soul and reminds me of my days as a young girl. That childhood nostalgia brought to life with a few wholesome ingredients. A combination of corn flour, fruit, and Real California Milk. I look for the Real California Milk seal to ensure I am choosing dairy products made with sustainably sourced milk from California dairy family farms. Knowing this makes my morning that much better and I’m ready to meet the day.
 
#Ad #RealCaliforniaMilk #Atole #easyrecipe @realcalifmilk 

For more holiday recipe inspiration, visit:
https://www.realcaliforniamilk.com/recipes
 
 
 
Creamy Banana Atole
3 cups of water
1 cinnamon stick
1 tablespoon vanilla extract
1 cup corn flour + 1 ½ cups water
4 Bananas (mashed/pureed
3 cups Real California Milk
1/3 cup Cane Sugar
 
 
Bring water, cinnamon, and vanilla to a boil over a medium heat. 
 
Whisk corn flour, and water together until smooth. Pour corn flour mixture through a sieve into water cinnamon mixture. This will act as your thickening agent. Continue whisking until corn flour mixture thickens to a pudding-like consistency. This will take about 5 minutes. 
 
Mash bananas in a bowl, then add them into the corn flour mixture until combined. Lower heat to medium low. 
 
Pour in Real California Milk and whisk. For your desired consistency, reduce amount of milk if you like your atole thick or add more milk for a thinner texture. Allow milk to warm, then whisk in sugar. Mix until sugar dissolves.
 
Allow mixture to cook for an additional five minutes before serving.

Tamal de Elote Dulce:
 
3 lbs. Masa Dulce de Elote from @northgatemarket 
3 Anaheim Chiles
12 – 2 inch pieces of melting cheese
Hojas de Maiz
1 cup black beans
½ cup crema
1/3 cup queso fresco, crumbled
 
Roast Chiles on an open flame  until charred. Place in an airtight container for 20 minutes, and allow chiles to sweat in their own heat. Remove chiles from airtight container and scrape off charred skin with a butter knife. Remove stem and seeds, and slice into strips.
 
Soak hojas (corn husks) in hot water for a minimum of 40 minutes. This will help the cornhusks become pliable. Remove from hot water and drain in a sieve.
 
Take a heaping tablespoon of sweet corn masa, and spread it inside of the cornhusk. Then add a 2 inch piece of your favorite melting cheese to the center along with a few chile strips.
 
Fold the corn husk as demonstrated in the video.
 
Steam in a tamalera over a high heat for 1 hour.
 
Serve with black beans (recipe below), crema, and crumbled queso fresco.
 
Black Beans:
 
1 lb. dried Black beans-  remove broken beans or Little Rocks and rinse beans thoroughly.
1/2 large onion
1 tablespoon Olive oil
A head of garlic
8 cups water
1 sprig epazote
1 tablespoon salt
 
Add beans, onion, olive oil, garlic, water and espazote to a slow cooker.
Cook for 8 to 10 hours. Once cooked add in salt and allow to rest for 30 minutes before serving.
 
Optional: Heat olive oil in a large frying pan. Scoop out black beans with a slotted spoon and fry in hot oil. Smash beans with a bean masher. Once beans are smashed add in liquid beans cooked in 1/2 cup at a time until desired consistency.

There’s something about having an easy dessert recipe up your sleeve that can be prepared with very little effort. These ultra delicious baked pears are just that, effortless. I poach the pears first to perfume them with sweetness and then bake with a dollop of jam in the center. Once baked I pair them with the creamiest companion, @parmalatusa Nata. The Nata gives these spiced pears a soft luscious milky bite. I drizzle honey on top and a sprinkle of pistachios. This is an elegant dessert to serve at a fancy holiday table that is the easiest to make.
 
Baked Pears with Creamy Nata:
 
4 Bosc Pears
6 ½ cups apple cider
½ cup brown sugar
1 teaspoon vanilla paste or extract
½ cup strawberry jam or jam of choice
12 oz. Parmalat Nata
¼ cup honey
¼ cup chopped pistachios
 
Peel pears and cut in half length wise.
Scoop out seeds using a small spoon or melon baller.
 
In a large pot pour in apple cider, sugar and vanilla paste. Bring to a boil.
Add in pear halves and allow to boil for 15 minutes to soften.
 
Preheat oven to 375 degrees Fahrenheit.
 
Remove pears from cider bath and place on a cooling rack for 10 minutes to cool and dry a little.
 
Place pears in a baking dish with pocket side up. Fill each pear pocket with 1 tablespoon of strawberry jam.
 
Bake for 25 minutes.
 
Scoop 3 heaping tablespoons of Parmalat Nata into a bowl. Place baked pear on top. Drizzle with ½ tablespoon of honey, and ½ tablespoon of chopped pistachios.
 
Serve and Enjoy!

I think my favorite time of the year is hands down Rosca Season. It’s only here for a limited amount of time so I try and make it as special as possible. If you are wondering how that is even possible…. Let me share the secret of adding Nata Chocolate as the relleno to the center of your Rosca and how it takes the experience to the next level.
 
I use @parmalatusa Nata and melted chocolate to make my mousse like dreamy Chocolate Nata. Once it’s combined I add it to the food processor to whip it into fluffy perfection.
I use it as the filling to my Rosca but can be used in the center of a cake as well.
 
You gotta try this Nata Chocolate! You’ll love what you end up with.
 
Chocolate Nata for Rosca Relleno
 
2 cups semi sweet chocolate
12 oz. Parmalat Nata
1/8 teaspoon ground cinnamon
1 tablespoon milk
 
Melt chocolate chips in a double boiler until completely melted. Mixing constantly until smooth.
 
Remove bowl from heat and allow melted chocolate to cool for 15 minutes.
 
Mix Parmalat Nata, cinnamon, and milk into melted cooled chocolate until completely combined.
 
Place in in a food processor for 1 minute to whip mixture.
 
Remove from food processor and place in a piping bag fitted with a star tip.
 
Chocolate Nata is now ready to pipe into your Rosca De Reyes.
 
Tip: If you buy the mini rosca they do not have babies in them. :)

As a child, I didn’t understand why; I just knew we would celebrate with a Rosca De Reyes, so I never questioned it. 

As an adult, I carry on this lovely tradition. My nativity scene stays up along with my tree until January 6th, celebrating the three kings. The only difference is I start enjoying Rosca De Reyes the second @northgatemarket begins selling them. I have them for Posadas, Navidad, while I watch a good movie, breakfast … anytime is a good time for a delicious Rosca. 

On January 6th, I invite family and friends over for the big party-sized Rosca De Reyes, hoping I get the baby so I can have another reason to eat Tamales on Feb.2nd. We all scream with excitement as each person takes their turn strategically navigating where the baby might not be. It’s such a festive way to bookend a fantastic holiday season and try all the Rosca De Reyes flavors Northgate offers. This year Northgate Gonzalez Market will hide a golden baby figurine in one Rosca and a Red colored baby figurine in one Rosca per location.
